This document reviews the acceptable use conditions of new and extended uses for the plant protection product Switch (A9219B) required for registration in the Netherlands and should be reviewed in conjunction with the core assessment and national assessment of the the re-registration of this product.

The new and extended uses and extended uses for A9219B are presented in the GAP table (please refer to 2.3).


This document is based on the information of Part A, re-registration in the Netherlands of A9219B, (August 2010). The new and extended uses of A9219B have no effect on the information presented in Part A, other than the GAP table.



PART A – Risk Management

This document describes the acceptable use conditions required for the re-registration in the Netherlands of A9219B containing:

  • 375 g/kg Cyprodinil which was included into Annex I of Council Directive 91/414/EEC (Commission Directive 2006/64/CE of 18 July 2006)

  • 250 g/kg Fludioxonil which was included into Annex I of Council Directive 91/414/EEC (Commission Directive 2007/76/EC; 20 December 2007)

The risk assessment conclusions are based on the information, data and assessments provided in Registration Report, Part B Sections 1-7 and Part C and where appropriate the addenda for the Netherlands. The information, data and assessments provided in Registration Report, Parts B include assessment of further data or information as required at national re registration by the EU review. It also includes assessment of data and information relating to A9219B where that data have not been considered in the EU review process. Otherwise assessments for the safe use of A9219B have been made using endpoints agreed in the EU review of fludioxonil or cyprodinil.

This document describes the specific conditions of use and labelling required for the Netherlands for the re-registration of A9219B.

Appendix 1 of this document provides a copy of the final product authorisation for the Netherlands.

Appendix 2 of this document is a copy of the approved product label for the Netherlands.

1.Details of the application

1.1.Application background

This application was submitted by Syngenta.

The application was for approval of A9219B, a WG containing 375 g/kg cyprodinil and 250 g/kg fludioxonil and for use as a fungicide in a wide range of crops.

1.2.Annex I inclusion

Cyprodinil

The inclusion of cyprodinil on Annex I of Directive 91/414/EEC entered into force on 1 May 2007 according to Commission Directive 2006/64/CE.

For the implementation of the uniform principles of Annex VI, the conclusions of the review report on the cyprodinil, and in particular Appendices I and II thereof, as finalised in the Standing Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health in EFSA Scientific Report (2005) 51, 1 78 have been taken into account.

The Annex I Inclusion Directive for cyprodinil (2006/64/CE) provides specific provisions which need to be considered by the applicant in the preparation of their submission and by the MS prior to granting an authorisation:

  • Particular attention should be given to the safety of operators and ensure that conditions of use prescribe the application of adequate personal protective equipment;

  • Particular attention should be given to the protection of birds, mammals and aquatic organisms. Conditions of authorisation should include risk mitigation measures, such as buffer zones.

  • Further studies should be submitted to confirm the risk assessment for birds and mammals and for possible presence of residues of metabolite CGA304075 in food of animal origin.

These concerns were all addressed in the submission.

Fludioxonil

The inclusion of fludioxonil on Annex I of Directive 91/414/EEC entered into force on 1 November 2008 according to the Commission Directive 2007/76/EC, 20 December 2007.

For the implementation of the uniform principles of Annex VI, the conclusions of the review report on fludioxonil, and in particular Appendices I and II thereof, as finalised in the Standing Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health on EFSA Scientific Report (2007) 110, 1-85, have been taken into account.

The Annex I Inclusion Directive for fludioxonil (2007/76/EC) provides specific provisions under Part B which need to be considered by the applicant in the preparation of their submission and by the MS prior to granting an authorisation:

In assessing applications to authorise plant protection products containing fludioxonil for uses other than seed treatment, Member States shall pay particular attention to the criteria in Article 4 (1)(b), and shall ensure that any necessary data and information is provided before such an authorisation is granted and:

  • Must pay particular attention to the potential for groundwater contamination, in particular from soil photolysis metabolites CGA399833 and CGA192155, in vulnerable zones,

  • Must pay particular attention to the protection of fish and aquatic invertebrates.

Conditions of authorisation should include risk mitigation measures, where appropriate.

These concerns were all addressed in the submission.

1.3.Regulatory approach

To obtain re-approval the product A9219B must (where appropriate) meet the conditions of Annex I inclusion and be supported by dossiers satisfying the requirements of Annex II and Annex III, with an assessment to Uniform Principles, using Annex I agreed endpoints.

This application was submitted in order to allow the re-registration of an already approved product in the Netherlands in accordance with the above.

1.4.Data protection claims

Where protection for data is being claimed for information supporting registration of A9219B, it is indicated in the reference lists in Appendix 1 of the Registration Report, Part B Sections 1 7.

1.5.Letters of Access

Where Syngenta has provided the supporting data in Document K, the ownership of the data is indicated in the reference lists in Appendix 1 of the Registration Report, Part C and Part B Sections 1-7 and in Appendix 3 of Part A.

Explanation:

Hazard symbol:

Xi is obligatory when R43 is assigned.

Risk phrases:

R43: The formulation was negative in two Buehler tests for skin sensitisation in the guinea pig. In addition, the formulation was negative in a Maximisation test. However, in the evaluation of this test in the DAR it was concluded that an insufficient amount of animals was used. Based on the amount of cyprodinil it is proposed to label the preparation as ‘May cause sensitisation by skin contact (R43)’. The R phrase 43 is optional for packaging below 125 mL.

Safety phrases:

S2, S13 and S20 are not obligatory for formulations intended for professional use only.


The Ctgb only assigns S35 to preparations with hazard-symbol T+, T, or C with respect to the toxicological aspect of the preparation in question.


S36/37 is invariably assigned by the Ctgb to all formulations labelled with Xi, R43 and is also assigned based on the risk assessment and therefore not optional for small packages.


S57 is not compulsory in combination with the assigned R phrases.


S60 and S61 are assigned to products for professional use labelled N, R50/53. S60 and S61are optional for small packages (< 125 mL).

3.Risk management

3.1.Reasoned statement of the overall conclusions taken in accordance with the Uniform Principles

3.1.1.Physical and chemical properties (Part B, Section 1, Points 2 and 4)

The product A9219B is a water dispersible granule (WG). All studies have been performed in accordance with the current requirements, the critical GAP and the results are deemed to be acceptable. The appearance of the product is that of a light brown solid, with a weak, uncharacteristic odour. It is not explosive, has no oxidising properties and is not a self heating substance. In aqueous solution, it has a pH value around 9. The stability data support a shelf life of at least two years at ambient temperature. The technical characteristics of A9219B are acceptable for a water dispersible granule formulation.

According to Directive 1999/45/EC as amended, the proposed labelling for physico-chemical properties for A9219B is: None.

Compliance with FAO specifications: The product A9219B complies with FAO specifications.

Compatibility of mixtures: No data have been provided regarding the physical and chemical compatibility of tank mixes.

Nature and characteristics of the packaging: Packaging proposed for A9219B is 100, 160, 200, 300, 400 g and 1, 5, 10, 45, 400 kg containers. Information/data on packaging type, dimensions, capacity, size of opening, type of closure, resistance to and compatibility with the contents of the packaging, have been submitted, evaluated and are considered to be acceptable.

Nature and characteristics of the protective clothing and equipment: Information regarding the required protective clothing and equipment for the safe handling of A9219B has been provided and is considered to be acceptable.

3.1.2.Methods of analysis (Part B, Section 2, Point 5)

3.1.2.1.Analytical method for the formulation (Part B, Section 2, Point 5.2)

A9219B was a representative formulation in the EU review of fludioxonil. Analytical methods for determination of fludioxonil and cyprodinil, impurities and relevance of CIPAC methods in A9219B were evaluated as part of the EU review of fludioxonil. All data are considered adequate.

3.1.2.2.Analytical methods for residues (Part B, Section 2, Points 5.3 – 5.8)

Methods for crops and animal products: All crop and animal product analytical methods are active substance data and are required in support of the setting of EU MRLs, MSs are invited to comment as part of the EU MRL setting process (in the framework of Regulation (EC) 396/2005). Adequate EU MRLs for the uses of A9219B are in place. No further review is required.

Methods for soil, water and air: All analytical methods are active substance data and were evaluated during the EU review by RMS Denmark. Additional data on methods/validation in soil and water for cyprodinil and fludioxonil have been developed and have been provided. All data are considered adequate.

Methods for body fluids and tissues: Cyprodinil and fludioxonil are not classified as toxic or highly toxic, therefore analytical methods for the determination of residues in body fluids and tissue are not required.



3.1.3.Mammalian Toxicology (Part B, Section 3, Point 7)

3.1.3.1.Acute Toxicity (Part B, Section 3, Point 7.1)

A9219B was a representative formulation in the EU review of fludioxonil. All acute toxicity data on A9219B were considered adequate.

A9219B containing 375 g/kg cyprodinil and 250 g/kg fludioxonil has a low toxicity in respect to acute oral, dermal and inhalation toxicity studies in the rat and is not irritating to the rabbit eye and skin. A9219B was shown not to be a skin sensitizer to the guinea pig in three skin sensitization studies (2 Buehler tests and 1 maximisation test). It was shown to be a moderate sensitizer in one maximisation test that was shown to have methodological shortcomings.

3.1.3.2.Operator Exposure (Part B, Section 3, Point 7.3)

For mechanical downward spraying in the field and for the greenhouse application it can be concluded that, based on the risk assessment, no adverse health effects are expected for the unprotected operator after dermal and respiratory exposure to cyprodinil and fludioxonil as a result of the application of Switch in the intended crops.


For the unprotected operator, adverse health effects after dermal/respiratory exposure to cyprodinil as a result of mechanical/manual upward field applications of Switch cannot be excluded. Correct use of personal protective equipment will reduce the dermal exposure and results in a sufficient reduction of the exposure to cyprodinil for these type of applications of Switch in the intended crops.


These conclusions also apply for combined exposure to cyprodinil and fludioxonil.


3.1.3.3.Bystander Exposure (Part B, Section 3, Point 7.4)

It is concluded that there is no undue risk of residential exposure or to the bystander after incidental short-term exposure to Switch.



3.1.3.4.Worker Exposure (Part B, Section 3, Point 7.5)

Based on the risk assessment, it can be concluded that no adverse health effects are expected for the unprotected worker after dermal and respiratory exposure during re-entry activities in the intended crops due to exposure to cyprodinil and fludioxonil after application of Switch.

3.1.5.Environmental fate and behaviour (Part B, Section 5, Point 9.1-9.3, 9.9)

Cyprodinil: The majority of the data presented were reviewed in the EU review. Additional new data are also provided in this submission, and appropriate endpoints were used to calculate PECS for A9219B and cyprodinil in soil, surface water, ground water and air for the intended use patterns.

Fludioxonil: The majority of the data presented were reviewed in the EU review. Additional new data are also provided in this submission, and appropriate endpoints were used to calculate PECS for A9219B and fludioxonil in soil, surface water, ground water and air for the intended use patterns.

3.1.5.1.Predicted Environmental Concentration in Soil (PECS) (Part B, Section 5, Points 9.4 and 9.5)

Cyprodinil: The PEC of A9219B and cyprodinil in soil (PECS) has been assessed with the FOCUS groundwater crop interception values, where appropriate, and the worst case DT50 values agreed in Annex Point IIIA 9.2 based on new data provided for this assessment. Based on the maximum critical EU recommended use rate of 4 x 288 g a.s./ha, the maximum initial predicted environmental concentration in soil (PECS) of cyprodinil will be 1.203 mg/kg (tulips). Assuming the same application regime is used year after year, it is predicted that a plateau concentration of cyprodinil in the soil will be reached after 11 years. This is predicted to be 0.754 mg/kg for tulips, based on the conservative, worst-case acidic field DT50 of 284 days.

The PEC of CGA249287, CGA275535 and CGA321915 in soil (PECS) has been assessed with the FOCUS groundwater crop interception values, where appropriate, and the worst case DT50 values established in the EU review or agreed in Annex Point IIIA 9.1 based on new calculations/data provided for this assessment. For metabolites CGA249287, CGA275535 and CGA321915 the proposed use pattern will lead to maximum initial PECS of 0.106 mg/kg, 0.048 mg/kg and 0.029 mg/kg for the use in tulips, respectively.

The results for PECS for the active substance and its metabolites were used for the ecotoxicological risk assessment.

Fludioxonil: The PEC of A9219B and fludioxonil in soil (PECS) has been assessed with the FOCUS groundwater crop interception values, where appropriate, and the worst case DT50 values established in the EU review. Based on the maximum EU recommended use rate of 4 x 181 g a.s./ha, the maximum initial predicted environmental concentration in soil (PECS) of fludioxonil will be 0.692 mg/kg for use in tulips.

The PEC of CGA192155, CGA265378 and CGA339833 in soil (PECS) has been assessed with the FOCUS groundwater crop interception values, where appropriate, and the worst case DT50 values established in the EU review. For metabolites CGA192155, CGA265378 and CGA339833 the critical EU use pattern will lead to maximum initial PECS of 0.060 mg/kg, 0.077 mg/kg and 0.061 mg/kg, respectively (reached in the proposed use in tulip).

The results for PECS for the active substance and its metabolites were used for the ecotoxicological risk assessment.

3.1.5.2.Predicted Environmental Concentration in Ground Water (PECGW) (Part B, Section 5, Point 9.6)

Cyprodinil: The PEC of cyprodinil, CGA249287, CGA275535 and CGA321915 in ground water (PECGW) has been assessed with standard FOCUS scenarios to obtain outputs from the FOCUS PELMO and FOCUS PEARL models and the DT50 and KFOC values established in the EU review or agreed in Annex Point IIIA 9.2 and 9.3 based on new data provided for this assessment. The cyprodinil groundwater assessment has been conducted using the worst-case acid field DT50 of 209 days. From the discussion under Annex Points IIIA 9.1 – IIIA 9.3, metabolites CGA249287, CGA275535 and CGA321915 are considered to be of relevance for groundwater assessment. In order to provide a conservative groundwater assessment for these metabolites, the EU agreed geomean of the laboratory data for the parent, cyprodinil, was used, 27 days.

Cyprodinil has a low mobility in soil and therefore the risk to ground water is expected to be minimal. The predicted environmental concentrations (PECGW) at 1m depth for cyprodinil following 20 years use on pome/stone fruit and soft fruit at 3 x 375 g a.s./ha with 65% foliar interception, were less than 0.001 g/L in all scenarios using FOCUS-PELMO and FOCUS PEARL and a DT50 of 209 days. For vines at 2 x 450 g a.s./ha and 70% foliar interception the PECGW at 1m depth were less than 0.001 g/L in all scenarios. For leafy vegetables at 3 x 225 g a.s./ha with a 25%, 40% and 40% foliar interception and fruiting vegetables at 3 x 375 g a.s./ha and a 80% foliar interception and strawberries at 3 x 375g a.s./ha and a foliar interception of 60% the PECGW at 1m depth were less than 0.001 g/L in all scenarios. For bulb vegetables at 3 x 375 g a.s./ha with 25%, 25% and 40% foliar interception, Root vegetables at 3 x 375 g a.s./ha with 25%, 60% and 60% foliar interception, Legumes at 3 x 375 g a.s./ha and 70% foliar interception and Tobacco at 2 x 225 g a.s./ha and 90% foliar interception and tulips at 4 x 281 g a.s. /ha at 10%, 10%, 25% and 25% foliar interception. The PECGW at 1m depth were less than 0.001 g/L in all scenarios. The potential for the metabolites CGA249287, CGA275535 and CGA321915 to leach to groundwater has been assessed in the same way.

The models predict that cyprodinil and its metabolites CGA249287 and CGA275535 will not be found in ground water at concentrations greater than 0.1 μg/L. However, metabolite CGA321915 may leach to groundwater at concentrations smaller than 0.1 μg/L, but greater than 0.01 μg/L in the Kremsmünster scenario, as predicted using leaching model GeoPEARL. Therefore, based on the assessment, a restriction sentence for the use of Switch in groundwater protection area’s will be placed on the label:

Om het grondwater te beschermen mag dit product niet worden gebruikt in grondwaterbeschermingsgebieden



Fludioxonil: The PEC of fludioxonil, CGA265378, CGA339833 and CGA192155 in ground water (PECGW) has been assessed with standard FOCUS scenarios to obtain outputs from the FOCUS PELMO and FOCUS PEARL models and the KFOC values established in the EU review. From the discussion under Annex Points IIIA 9.1 – IIIA 9.3, metabolites CGA265378, CGA339833 and CGA192155 are considered to be of relevance for groundwater assessment.

Fludioxonil has a low mobility in soil and therefore the risk to ground water is expected to be minimal. The predicted environmental concentrations (PECGW) at 1m depth for fludioxonil following 20 years use on pome/stone fruit and soft fruit at 3 x 250 g as/ha with 65% foliar interception, were less than 0.001 g/L in all scenarios using FOCUS-PELMO and FOCUS PEARL and a DT50 of 164 days. For vines at 2 x 300 g as/ha and 70% foliar interception the PECGW at 1m depth were less than 0.001 g/L in all scenarios. For leafy vegetables at 3 x 150 g as/ha with a 25%, 40% and 40% foliar interception and fruiting vegetables at 3 x 250 g as/ha and a 80% foliar interception and strawberries at 3 x 300g as/ha and a foliar interception of 60% the PECGW at 1 m depth were less than 0.001 g/L in all scenarios. For bulb vegetables at 3 x 250 g as/ha with 25%, 25% and 40% foliar interception, root vegetables at 3 x 300 g as/ha with 25%, 60% and 60% foliar interception, legumes at 3 x 300 g as/ha and 70% foliar interception, tobacco at 2 x 150 g as/ha and 90% foliar interception and and tulips at 4 x 188 g a.s. /ha at 10%, 10%, 25% and 25% foliar interception. The PECGW at 1m depth were less than 0.001 g/L in all scenarios.

The models predicts that fludioxonil will not be found in ground water at concentrations greater than 0.1 μg/L. Based on the assessment, the use of fludioxonil is not expected to lead to leaching into groundwater at levels that would be unacceptable when applied according to the recommended use pattern.

The potential for the metabolites CGA265378, CGA339833 and CGA192155 to leach to groundwater has been assessed in the same way. Metabolites CGA192155 and CGA339833 are the only two metabolites which show a potential to exceed the limit of 0.1 g/L, as predicted by FOCUS modelling for the specified GAP. These metabolites were assessed via the stepwise process in the guidance document on the relevance of metabolites in groundwater (SANCO/221/2000) and shown to be non-relevant.

3.1.6.Ecotoxicology (Part B, Section 6, Point 10)

3.1.6.1.Effects on Terrestrial Vertebrates (Part B, Section 6, Points 10.1 and 10.3)

Birds

Although A9219B was assessed as a representative formulation in the EU review of fludioxonil, the effects on birds from all the critical uses proposed for A9219B have not been evaluated in either the EU review of the cyprodinil or fludioxonil. Therefore, all risk assessments and supporting data for A9219B with the proposed use pattern are provided and are considered adequate.

The risk assessment for effects on birds is carried out according to the latest EFSA Guidance document draft of the ‘EFSA Guidance Document on Risk Assessment for Birds and Mammals 20091.

The acute, short-term and long-term risks of A9219B to birds were assessed from toxicity exposure ratios between toxicity endpoints, estimated from studies with cyprodinil and fludioxonil, and maximum residues occurring on food items following applications according to the proposed use pattern. Risk of secondary poisoning has also been assessed, as both cyprodinil and fludioxonil have log POW values >3.0. (In the Part B Section 6 Addendum for the Netherlands, the assessments are re-visited with the national PECSW values and are considered adequate).

The TER values, calculated for recommended scenarios, all exceed the trigger values of 10 for acute and short-term risk and 5 for long-term risk (including secondary poisoning), indicating that the risk to birds is acceptable following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern.

Terrestrial vertebrates (other than birds)

Although A9219B was assessed as a representative formulation in the EU review of fludioxonil, the effects on mammals from all the critical uses proposed for A9219B have not been evaluated in either the EU review of the cyprodinil or fludioxonil. Therefore data on A9219B are evaluated, and risk assessments for A9219B with the proposed use pattern are provided and are considered adequate.

The acute and long-term risks of A9219B to wild mammals were assessed from toxicity exposure ratios between toxicity endpoints, estimated from studies with cyprodinil and fludioxonil, and maximum residues occurring on food items following applications according to the use pattern. Risk of secondary poisoning has also been assessed, as both substances have log POW values of >3.0. (In the Part B Section 6 Addendum for the Netherlands, the assessments are re-visited with the national PECSW values and are considered adequate)

The TER values, calculated for recommended scenarios, all exceed the trigger values of 10 for acute risk. For the long-term risk, the TERs exceed the trigger of 5 for most scenarios. For leafy crops, the TER for cyprodinil is 4.9 for voles and is consided acceptable. However when considering combination toxicology, the combined TER is 3.2 and a further assessment is required. When taking into account the exact application rate, the risk is acceptable when only one application occurs before BBCH 50. When considering two applications before BBCH 50, the TER is still below the combined TER is still 3.4. However, the also assuming an interception of 30% for growth stages 40-49, the Combined TER is 4.9. Taking into account that the risk assessment is still worst-case concerning PT, PD; and that the chronic endpoints showed no effects at the highest application ate; the risk is considered to be acceptable. An acceptable risk is expected for secondary poisoning. .

3.1.6.2.Effects on Aquatic Species (Part B, Section 6, Point 10.2)

Although A9219B was assessed as a representative formulation in the EU review of fludioxonil, the effects on aquatic organisms for A9219B according to the entire proposed EU GAP have not been evaluated. Data on A9219B are evaluated, and risk assessments for A9219B with the proposed critical EU use pattern are provided and are considered adequate.

In the Part B Section 6 Addendum for the Netherlands, the risk assessments for A9219B are provided with the endpoints from the Section 5 Addendum for the Netherlands.

Risk assessment for fish – For use in vines and pome/stone fruit, the risk to fish is acceptable following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern following implementation of drift reduction (1%).

Risk assessment for aquatic invertebrates – Higher tier refinement of the risk assessment was required for both cyprodinil and fludioxonil. For cyprodinil, endpoints from acute invertebrate tests were used to define a species sensitivity distribution (SSD), which allows the level of risk to be assessed probabilistically. Also, two mesocosm studies were conducted. For fludioxonil, one mesocosm was conducted. For use in vines and pome/stone fruit, the risk to aquatic invertebrates is acceptable following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern following implementation of drift reduction (1%).

Risk assessment for algae - For use in vines and pome/stone fruit, the risk to algae is acceptable following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern following implementation of drift reduction (1%).

In conclusion, acceptable risk to aquatic organisms was achieved for use in vines and pome/stone fruit following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern following implementation of drift reduction (1%). Mitigation is not required for the other crop groupings.

Studies of the acute toxicity of A9219B for fish, daphnia and algae showed that this product should be labelled as very toxic for aquatic organisms, due to its toxicity to fish/daphnia/algae. Hence, phrases R50/53 very toxic to aquatic organisms, may cause long term adverse effects in the aquatic environment should be added to the product label.

3.1.6.3.Effects on Bees and Other Arthropod Species (Part B, Section 6, Points 10.4 and 10.5)

Bees

Although A9219B was assessed as a representative formulation in the EU review of fludioxonil, the effects on bees from all the critical uses proposed for A9219B have not been evaluated in either the EU review of the cyprodinil or fludioxonil. Therefore data on A9219B are evaluated, and these risk assessments for A9219B with the proposed critical EU use pattern are considered adequate.

The risk of A9219B to honey-bees was assessed from hazard quotients between toxicity endpoints, estimated from acute oral and contact studies with cyprodinil, fludioxonil and A9219B, and the maximum EU single application rate of 1200 g formulation/ha (450 g cyprodinil/ha and 300 g fludioxonil/ha).

All the hazard quotients for cyprodinil and fludioxonil are less than 50, indicating that the risk to bees is acceptable following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern.

Other non-target arthropods

Effects on non-target arthropods other than bees for A9219B have not been evaluated as part of the EU review for cyprodinil but was included in the fludioxonil EU review. The conclusion of the EU review was that effects for fludioxonil formulated as A9219B, were below the Annex VI trigger of 30% indicating that A9219B is acceptable. However, the critical EU GAP is more extensive that provided for EU review and therefore data on A9219B are evaluated, and risk assessments for A9219B with the proposed critical EU use pattern are provided and are considered adequate.

The in-field HQ values were above the trigger value indicating potential risk to in-field non target arthropods following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern. The risk assessment was refined using higher tier studies, namely extended laboratory (some including an aged-residue component) and semi field studies were conducted. By comparing the lethal and sublethal endpoints from these higher tier studies with the predicted environmental rate of the test substance it was concluded that the risk to in-field non-target arthropods is acceptable following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern.

Off-crop, the HQ values are below the trigger value indicating that the risk to off-crop non-target arthropods is acceptable following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern.

3.1.6.4.Effects on Earthworms and Other Soil Marco-organisms (Part B, Section 6, Point 10.6)

Although A9219B was assessed as a representative formulation in the EU review of fludioxonil, the effects on earthworms and other soil non-target macro-organisms for all the critical EU uses of A9219B, and taking account of new data provided in this submission, have not been evaluated as part of the EU review for cyprodinil or fludioxonil. Data on A9219B are therefore evaluated, and risk assessments for A9219B with the proposed use pattern are provided and are considered adequate.

Earthworms

The acute and long-term risk of A9219B to earthworms was assessed from acute and long-term toxicity exposure ratios (TERs) between the selected toxicity endpoints for cyprodinil, fludioxonil and their metabolites, and the maximum PECS.

The acute and chronic TER values for cyprodinil, fludioxonil and their metabolites are greater than the Annex IV triggers of 10 and 5, respectively, indicating that the risk to earthworms is acceptable following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern.

Other soil non-target macro-organisms

The risk of A9219B to other non-target soil macro-organisms, as represented by Folsomia candida, was assessed from toxicity exposure ratios (TERs) between the toxicity endpoints and the maximum PECS.

The TER value is greater than the recommended trigger of 5, indicating that the risk to soil macro-organisms, as represented by F. candida, is acceptable following use of A9219B according to the proposed use pattern.

3.1.6.5.Effects on organic matter breakdown (Part B, Section 6, Point 10.6.7)

Cyprodinil and fludioxonil have been shown to pose a low risk to earthworms, micro-organisms and other soil macro-organisms (collembola); all organisms involved in organic matter breakdown in the field. In addition, the respective DT90 field for cyprodinil (in neutral to alkaline soils) and fludioxonil are < 365 days. Cyprodinil and fludioxonil are therefore not expected to pose an unacceptable risk to organic matter breakdown following the recommended use of A9219B and no litterbag study is required. However, it has been demonstrated that cyprodinil is potentially more persistent in acidic soils therefore a litterbag study has been conducted for cyprodinil in acidic soil conditions.

The risk of cyprodinil and fludioxonil to organic matter decomposition was evaluated by comparison of the PECS with no-effect concentrations from a litter-bag test with A9219B.

The NOEC value for cyprodinil and fludioxonil are approximately 1.7- and 5-fold greater than the corresponding PECS values, respectively; indicating that cyprodinil and fludioxonil in A9219B do not pose an unacceptable risk to organic matter breakdown.

3.1.6.6.Effects on Soil Non-target Micro-organisms (Part B, Section 6, Point 10.7)

Although A9219B was assessed as a representative formulation in the EU review of fludioxonil, the effects on soil microbial activity from all the EU critical uses proposed for A9219B have not been evaluated in either the EU review of the cyprodinil or fludioxonil. Therefore data on A9219B are evaluated, and risk assessments for A9219B with the proposed EU use pattern are provided and are considered adequate.

The risk of A9219B to soil micro-organisms was evaluated by comparison of no effect concentrations, derived from laboratory tests, with PECS.

All no effect levels exceed the relevant PECS values by a factor of at least 2, indicating that A9219B does not pose an unacceptable risk to soil micro-organisms.

3.1.6.7.Assessment of Potential for Effects on Other Non-target Organisms (Flora and Fauna) (Part B, Section 6, Point 10.8)

Non-Target Plants - Terrestrial

Although A9219B was assessed as a representative formulation in the EU review of fludioxonil, the effects on non-target terrestrial plants from all the EU critical uses proposed for A9219B have not been evaluated in either the EU review of the cyprodinil or fludioxonil. Therefore data on A9219B are evaluated, and risk assessments for A9219B with the proposed EU use pattern are provided and are considered adequate.

No studies with the formulation are available. The available tests with different formulations showed no effects at any application rate. Unfortunately these application rates were too low to give TERs > 5. Data from the efficacy section show that no to very limited effects are found in a very wide variety of crops, when exposed to single application rates. Worst-case TERs based on these screening rates are > 3.0 (pome fruits) and > 4.0 (grape) and > 5 for all other crops. Considering the large amount of species tested, the risk is considered to be acceptable.



Non-Target Plants - Aquatic

Tests on aquatic plants are not required as A9219B is not a herbicide, however aquatic plant data were considered in the EU review for fludioxonil and cyprodinil and an assessment of the effects of A9219B on aquatic plants is provided and is adequate.

Other non-target species (Flora and Fauna)

Tests on other non-target species are not required.

Implications for labelling resulting from ecotoxicological assessment:

A9219B is classified as N; R50/53 according to Directive 1999/45/EC as amended, based on aquatic toxicity data for the product. As a plant protection product, the instructions for use should be followed to avoid risks to man and the environment

Mitigation measures (drift reduction) is required for the use in apple and pome fruit. For IPM uses a warning sentence should be included on the label. See below (in Dutch):



Om in het water levende organismen te beschermen is de toepassing in de teelt van appel, peer, kers, pruim en druif in percelen die grenzen aan oppervlaktewater uitsluitend toegestaan na 1 mei en indien gebruik gemaakt wordt van één van de volgende maatregelen:

    • er gespoten wordt met een tunnelspuit, of

    • er gebruik wordt gemaakt van een windhaag op de rand van het rijpad en éénzijdige bespuiting van de laatste bomenrij, of

    • er in de eerste 20 meter grenzend aan het oppervlaktewater gebruik wordt gemaakt van een venturi-dop in combinatie met een éénzijdige bespuiting van de laatste bomenrij.



Let op: dit middel kan schadelijk zijn voor natuurlijke vijanden. Raadpleeg uw leverancier van natuurlijke vijanden over het gebruik van dit middel in combinatie met het gebruik van natuurlijke vijanden.





3.1.7.Efficacy (Part B, Section 7, Point 8)

Re-registration of existing uses (see core dossier for evaluation)

It concerns the re-registration of Switch in The Netherlands for use in apple, pear, cherries, plums, currants, gooseberries, blueberries, grapes, strawberries, raspberries, blackberries, lettuce (except lambs lettuce), endive, fresh pulses (with and without pods), protected tomato, tulip, floriculture, tree nursery crops and perennials. For some of these crops trials have been submitted in the core BAD of Switch and have been evaluated in the core dossier. In the core dossier the tested uses were positively evaluated. As for re-registration not all uses need to be tested, the data generated with the tested uses can be extrapolated to the non-tested uses.

As a consequence, it was concluded that based on the trial results and expert judgement, Switch is effective as a fungicide in the control of various diseases in a range of crops and that the application does not give adverse side effects to an unacceptable level when applied according to Good Agricultural Practices. However, in protected tomato and protected floriculture phytotoxicity was recorded. A warning sentence should be included on the label text recommending small scale test sprays if no experience is gained yet with the crop varieties to be treated.


The re-registration of Switch for the currently claimed uses has been confirmed.


New and extended uses (see national addendum for evaluation)


Fresh and dry harvested pulses

For the extension of the control of Ascochyta spp. (9 trials) and Mycosphaerella spp. (8 trials) in dry harvested pulses and fresh pulses (with and without pods) trials have been carried out in the Maritime zone and were submitted in the core BAD.

In the trials, the evaluated dose rate of 1.0 kg Switch per ha gave moderate levels of control of Ascochyta spp.. The level of control was comparable to or better than that given by the reference product.

The evaluated dose rate of 1.0 kg Switch per ha generally gave low-to-moderate levels of control of Mycosphaerella pinodes. The level of control was generally comparable to that given by the reference product.

Based on the trial results and expert judgement, it can be concluded that Switch is effective as a fungicide for the control of Ascochyta pisi and Mycosphaerella pinodes in pea and for the control of Botrytis and Sclerotinia in bean and pea. Extrapolation of the effectiveness against these diseases in pea (and bean) is possible to all fresh pulses and dry harvested pulses. All crop species belong to the same Leguminoseous family and the difference in dry and fresh pulses is based only the on varieties and method of cultivation. The plant architecture, crop development and plant-pathogen interaction are comparable among all species and for all purposes of cultivation. This is also applicable for the aspect of crop safety and it can be concluded that the application does not give adverse side effects to an unacceptable level when applied according to Good Agricultural Practices in fresh pulses and dry harvested pulses.


Apple and pear

For the extension of the control of Gloeosporium rot in apple and pear, 17 trials have been carried out in the Maritime zone and were submitted in the core BAD.

In apple, the evaluated dose rate of 0.8-1.0 kg Switch per ha gave a variable level of control. The level of control was comparable to or better than that given by the reference product based on tolylfluanide.

In pear, in 5 out of 7 trials no disease was present or the disease pressure was too low to make an evaluation possible. The evaluated dose rate of 0.8-1.0 kg Switch per ha gave a moderate levels of control in the 2 trials. The level of control was comparable to or better than that given by the reference product based on tolylfluanide.


Based on the trial results and expert judgement, it can be concluded that Switch is effective as a fungicide for the control of Gloeosporium spp. in apple and pear and that the application does not give adverse side effects to an unacceptable level when applied according to Good Agricultural Practices


Carrot

In the trials in carrot, the proposed dose rate of 0.8 kg/ha Switch gave in general moderate to variable levels of control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum and Alternaria dauci. However, the control given by Switch was in all trials at least comparable to and often better than the control given by the reference product. In the effectiveness trials, Switch at a dose rate of 0.8 kg/ha did not show any phytotoxicity to the carrot crop. In addition to the trial results it needs to be mentioned that Switch has an authorisation for the control of both fungi in carrot at a dose rate of 0.8 kg/ha in the United Kingdom.

Based on the trial results and expert judgement, it can be concluded that Switch is effective as a fungicide for the control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum and Alternaria dauci in carrot and that the application does not give adverse side effects to an unacceptable level when applied according to Good Agricultural Practices.


Celeriac

In the trials in celeriac, the proposed dose rate of 0.8 kg/ha Switch gave in general moderate to variable levels of control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum. However, the control given by Switch was in all trials at least comparable to and often better than the control given by the reference product. In the effectiveness trials, Switch at a dose rate of 0.8 kg/ha did not show any phytotoxicity to the celeriac crop. In addition to the trial results it needs to be mentioned that Switch has an authorisation for the control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum in celeriac at a dose rate of 0.8 kg/ha in the United Kingdom.

Based on the trial results and expert judgement, it can be concluded that Switch is effective as a fungicide for the control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum in celeriac and that the application does not give adverse side effects to an unacceptable level when applied according to Good Agricultural Practices.


Witloof chicory

For the extended use in the forcery of witloof chicory for the control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum 5 trials were carried out from 2008 till 2010 in The Netherlands (4 trials) and Belgium (1). Switch was applied at the proposed dose rate of 36 g/1000 kg roots during the cold storing of the chicory roots prior to forcery.

It was generally found that Switch showed significant control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum on roots and heads of witloof chicory when applied during the cold storing. The number of infected roots was decreased and the number of healthy, marketable heads was increased as compared to the untreated control. Application of Switch to the roots did not have a negative impact on crop stand.

The control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum given by Switch was generally significantly better than given by reference Contans WG and the untreated control and significantly less than the control given by reference Rovral Aquaflo.

Based on the trial results, expert judgement and the fact that Switch has an authorisation in witloof chicory in Belgium for the same use, it is justified to conclude that Switch is effective as a fungicide for the control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum in the forcery of witloof chicory and that the application does not give adverse side effects to an unacceptable level when applied according to Good Agricultural Practices.


Protected fruiting vegetables of Solanaceae

Currently, Switch has a registration for the control of Botryotinia fuckeliana in tomato. According to the extrapolation document “Possibilities for extrapolation of efficacy and crop safety of crop protection products”(CTB, May 2004) and based on expert judgement, extrapolation of effectiveness data is possible from protected tomato to protected fruiting vegetables of Solanaceae.

An extension of its use to protected solanaceae is intended. In order to do so 4 additional crop safety trials were conducted in protected eggplant in The Netherlands in 2009 and 2010. In the trials Switch was applied 3 times at the proposed dose rate of 80 g/hl and at the double dose rate of 160 g/hl.

In the trials 3 applications with Switch can cause phytotoxicity and visible residues to the leaves, especially when the plants are young and when applications are made under limited light conditions. In other periods of the year and on older plants no phytotoxicity and visible residues occurred. In all trials conducted no phytotoxicity and visible residues were found on stems and fruits. Although phytotoxicity was found in some trials crop stand was never influenced negatively and did not differ from the untreated control and reference Rovral Aquaflo. Crop safety data generated in protected eggplant can be extrapolated to all protected fruiting vegetables of Solanaceae.

Based on the trial results, expert judgement, extrapolation possibilities and the experience with Switch in practice in the past, it can be used safely on protected solanaceae. However, on the product label should be stated that phytotoxicity on the leaves might occur when Switch is applied on young plants under limited light conditions.


Protected fruiting vegetables of Cucurbitaceae

Currently, Switch has a registration for the control of Botryotinia fuckeliana in tomato.According to the extrapolation document “Possibilities for extrapolation of efficacy and crop safety of crop protection products”(CTB, May 2004) and based on expert judgement, extrapolation of effectiveness data is possible from protected tomato to protected fruiting vegetables of Cucurbitaceae.


The extended use of Switch for the control of Botryotinia fuckeliana in protected cucurbitaceae is new.

Therefore, 8 crop safety trials were conducted in protected cucumber in The Netherlands in 2009 and 2010. In the trials Switch was applied 3 times at the proposed dose rate of 80 g/hl and at the double dose rate of 160 g/hl.

In the trials 3 applications with Switch can cause some phytotoxicity and visible residues to the leaves, especially when the plants are young and when applications are made under limited light conditions. In other periods of the year and on older plants no phytotoxicity and visible residues occurred. In all trials conducted no phytotoxicity and visible residues were found on stems and fruits. Although some phytotoxicity was found in some trials crop stand was never influenced negatively and did not differ from the untreated control and reference Rovral Aquaflo. Crop safety data generated in protected cucumber can be extrapolated to all protected fruiting vegetables of Cucurbitaceae.

Based on the trial results, expert judgement, extrapolation possibilities and the experience with Switch in practice in the past, it can be used safely on protected cucurbitaceae. However, on the product label should be stated that some phytotoxicity on the leaves might occur when Switch is applied on young plants under limited light conditions.


New uses in minor crops

For the control of Botryotinia fuckeliana in protected lambs lettuce, radish, herbs and nursery and seed production of arable, vegetable and fruit crops, herbs and ornamentals no trials have been submitted. As these crops are listed as minor crops in The Netherlands, these uses can be claimed on the label of Switch through a so called “VUG”. In this case no effectiveness data need to be submitted and these uses can be claimed on the product label of Switch as far as it concerns effectiveness.


Overall conclusion

Based on the presented data, extrapolation possibilities and expert judgement it can be concluded that Switch is effective for the control of Ascochyta pisi, Mycosphaerella pinodes, Botrytis and Sclerotinia in fresh pulses and dry harvested pulses, the control of Gloeosporium spp. in apple and pear, the control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum and Alternaria dauci in carrot, the control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum in celeriac, the control of Sclerotinia sclerotiorum in the forcery of witloof chicory, the control of Botryotinia fuckeliana in protected fruiting vegetables of Solanaceae and the control of Botryotinia fuckeliana in protected fruiting vegetables of Cucurbitaceae.

The application of Switch in the various crops does not give adverse side effects to an unacceptable level when applied according to Good Agricultural Practices. However, on the product label should be stated that phytotoxicity on the leaves might occur when Switch is applied on young plants under limited light conditions in protected fruiting vegetables of Solanaceae and Cucurbitaceae.


The following restriction sentence is placed on the label:

“Na toepassing van Switch op jonge planten en onder slechte lichtcondities in de bedekte teelt van vruchtgroenten van Solanaceae en vruchtgroenten van Cucurbitaceae met eetbare schil kunnen fytotoxische reacties op het blad optreden.”

Algemeen

Switch heeft een preventieve werking tegen o.a. grauwe schimmel (Botryotinia fuckeliana).

Om de kans op het optreden van verminderde gevoeligheid te beperken, is het aan te bevelen Switch af te wisselen met andere voor Botryotinia fuckeliana bestrijding toegelaten middelen met een ander werkingsmechanisme.



Het middel heeft effect op niet-doelwit arthropoden, waaronder natuurlijke vijanden. Bij geïntegreerde teelten dient hiermee rekening gehouden te worden. Vermijd daarom onnodige blootstelling.

Er is voor deze toepassingen geen werkzaamheids- en fytotoxiciteitonderzoek uitgevoerd. Er wordt daarom aangeraden een proefbespuiting uit te voeren, voordat het middel gebruikt wordt.
